{"type":"message","id":"8b6e9fc3","parentId":"c6755272","timestamp":"2026-02-15T19:10:15.587Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Reflecting on Commit Failures**\n\nI'm tackling the initial commit failure. It seems the problem lies in the shell's handling of the `&&` operator. I'll need to separate the `git add` and `git commit` commands, or perhaps use semicolons if PowerShell is indeed the shell. Fortunately, the stress test files ran without a hitch and the results are recorded. The next step is to retry the git commit steps with the new knowledge.\n\n\n**Analyzing Git Commands**\n\nI've determined the issue with the `git add && git commit` commands; it's likely a PowerShell issue. I'll execute them separately now, as best practice dictates, after successfully running the stress tests. The tests themselves ran fine, and `docs/ACTIVE_CONTEXT.json` has the latency, OODA correction and domain isolation results, which all check out. After git, I'll need to confirm `git status` is clean before reporting back.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771182615346_218","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"git add src/"},"thoughtSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771182615455_219","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"git commit -m \"App: Stable baseline for v4.0 stress test\""}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"exec_1771182615582_220","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"git status --porcelain src/"}}],"api":"google-vertex","provider":"google-vertex","model":"gemini-3-pro-preview","usage":{"input":7032,"output":226,"cacheRead":5207,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":7258,"cost":{"input":0.014064,"output":0.002712,"cacheRead":0.0010414,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0178174}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1771182581878}}
